ories: payments (XRP and issued tokens), NFT operations (minting, burning, offers, transfers), DEX trades (OfferCreate, OfferCancel, AMM operations), trustline changes (TrustSet), escrow events (create, finish, cancel), check operations, and account-level changes like settings modifications and deletions."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How does webhook delivery work?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"When an XRPL transaction matches your configured filters, XRNotify normalizes the event, signs the payload with your webhook secret using HMAC-SHA256, and delivers it as an HTTPS POST to your endpoint. If delivery fails, XRNotify retries with exponential backoff (up to 10 attempts over 12 hours). Events that exhaust all retries are moved to a dead-letter queue for manual inspection and replay."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is XRNotify free?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"XRNotify offers a free tier with 1,000 events per month and 2 webhook endpoints — enough for testing and hobby projects. Paid plans start at $29/month (Starter: 50,000 events, 10 webhooks, WebSocket streaming) and $99/month (Pro: 500,000 events, 50 webhooks, priority delivery). Enterprise plans with custom SLAs are available on request."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I verify webhook signatures?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Every XRNotify webhook includes an X-XRNotify-Signature header containing an HMAC-SHA256 hash of the request body, computed using your webhook signing secret. To verify, compute the HMAC-SHA256 of the raw request body with your secret and compare it to the header value using a constant-time comparison function to prevent timing attacks."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Who built XRNotify?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"XRNotify was built by Ali Morgan, founder of Jonomor, a systems architecture studio focused on AI Visibility and real-time infrastructure intelligence. XRNotify is the XRPL instrumentation layer of the Jonomor ecosystem, which also includes Guard-Clause, MyPropOps, The Neutral Bridge, Evenfield, and H.U.N.I.E."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is XRNotify part of a larger ecosystem?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. XRNotify is part of the Jonomor ecosystem, a suite of interconnected software products built by Ali Morgan. Within the ecosystem, XRNotify serves as the real-time observation layer — detecting XRPL events at the point of origin before they flow through interpretation and operational layers in other Jonomor properties."}}]}0:["pQjrRFT3j-NbWRfetFzsE",[[["",{"children":["docs",{"children":["guides",{"children":["realtime-balance",{"children":["__PAGE__",{}]}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["docs",{"children":["guides",{"children":["realtime-balance",{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",["$","div",null,{"className":"min-h-screen bg-[#0a0a0f] text-white antialiased","children":[["$","nav",null,{"className":"border-b border-zinc-800/50","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-2 text-sm","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/docs","className":"text-zinc-500 hover:text-zinc-300 no-underline","children":"Docs"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-zinc-600","children":"/"}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/docs#guides","className":"text-zinc-500 hover:text-zinc-300 no-underline","children":"Guides"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-zinc-600","children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300","children":"Real-time Balance Updates"}]]}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/dashboard","className":"text-zinc-400 hover:text-white transition-colors text-sm no-underline","children":"Dashboard →"}]]}]}],["$","main",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block text-xs font-medium text-emerald-400 bg-emerald-500/10 border border-emerald-500/20 rounded px-2 py-0.5 mb-4","children":"Guides"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-3","children":"Real-time Balance Updates"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-zinc-400 text-lg leading-relaxed","children":"Push live XRP and token balance changes directly to browser clients the instant a payment lands on-chain — no polling required."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4","children":"Overview"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4","children":"There are two common approaches for delivering real-time balance data to your frontend:"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-3 mb-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-zinc-900 border border-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"text-sm font-medium text-white mb-1","children":"Approach 1 — Webhook-driven (this guide)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-zinc-400 text-xs leading-relaxed","children":"XRNotify pushes a payment event to your server. Your server updates the database and emits a Server-Sent Event (SSE) to connected browser clients. Near-instant latency, no wasted requests."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-zinc-900 border border-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"text-sm font-medium text-white mb-1","children":"Approach 2 — Client polling"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-zinc-400 text-xs leading-relaxed","children":"The frontend polls your balance API on a fixed interval. Simpler to implement but introduces latency equal to the poll interval and generates unnecessary requests."}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300 text-sm leading-relaxed","children":"This guide covers Approach 1: XRNotify webhook → server handler → SSE stream → React hook. The end result is a balance that updates on-screen within a few seconds of a payment confirming on-chain."}]]}],[